ulture. On the other hand, humor scholars claim that humorous discourse has its special, essential features that distinguish it from other discourses. The pragmatic solution to the issue of potential circularity of humor defined in terms of discourse and discourse in terms of humor seems only feasible, and thus there is a need to discuss the structure and mechanisms of humorous texts and humorous performances. The chapters in the present volume, contributed by leading scholars in the field of humor studies, address the issues from various theoretical perspectives, from contextual semantics through General Theory of Verbal Humor, cognitive linguistics, discourse studies, sociolinguistics, to Ontological Semantic Theory of Humor, providing an excellent overview of the field to novices and experts alike.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aWit and humor. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive Linguistics.  aHumor Studies.  aSociolinguistics.1 aAttardo, Salvatore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrzozowska, Dorota, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrzozowska, Dorota, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCain, Sarah Seewoester, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChlopicki, Wladyslaw, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChovanec, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChłopicki, Władysław, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKitazume, Sachiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLibura, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaskin, Victor, econt